f past, and you could - if you was there - up 'til six or after you could have pork pasties or chitteling or - whelks or anything like that, tea and drinks all on open stalls, everything open. But it was lovely. Fish, they used to - the fish, it used to b
e
 red eyed and fresh, brought in from the coast in the morning, and it was all fresh with the scales and - beautiful, yes. That's what puts me off of food these days is you look at it and - you know, you can always compare. And my daughter-in-law, she said
 
I'm far too fussy but - when you've been used to - and we used to have men come round when we were kids with a big wicker basket on their arms, selling kippers and bloaters. And crumpets. They used to come and call up your - right of way, we used to have 
a
 - you know, sideway, call up, and - your mother would buy all this fish or crumpets or something and cook for tea. Mm. Never had to go to the shop then you know, they used to come - up the streets. Wood people used to come selling wood. The gypsies used 
