busy and we used to pick the flowers and violets and - watch for the little moles and all things like that you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You enjoyed that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember any other sort of outings with your parents, any special ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 We used to go to the seaside for a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Which one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 We used to go Southend and places like that for a day's excursion. And always went on the water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 By train, by - train. They used to run excursions through in those days. For a 
very few shillings, I don't know how many, three, four, five I should imagine, no more. My mother used to take us all. We used to go on the boat 'cos I remember sitting on the beach once - when we were on a yacht at Southend, we couldn't have been above -
 
I - I don't think - any of us - could have been above twelve. Right from the youngest to the oldest, and - she sat and cried because there was a storm and the boat was swaying, she thought we was never coming back. But we always came home safe. And anothe
r
 thing we used to do when we went to Harpenden sometimes my mother used to - hire what they called the carrier, and it used to be a horse and cart that delivered - parcels and letters and things, you know, like the post would do now, in the motor vans, bu
t
 it used to be horses and carts, we used to hire that and for a few coppers would take us all on the - now what did they used to call them - it was a horse and a sort of a van, a canvas van, and we all used to either get - in the front or in seats inside.
 
A carrier they used to call them. No, it wasn't a brake, no, we used to go for outings on - always went to Sunday school - all the Sunday school outings in the - open brakes we used to go. My mother always came then. Used to run in the races and - you kno
w, she thought she could race us and we'd race her sort of style, ever such good sport like that. Mm.
