y
po - stuff and we always - did the plates and things. Then when films came in, you know, I had a film camera. I saved sixpences and had a - box film camera for eighteen and six I think it was. And of course we thought we was real good when we'd got a came
ra of our own, yes. In the first place I had a plate camera. And then I progressed to a film camera, and then we got to better cameras you know, and now - I've got two, neither of them are really much good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they have a choir at the Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were you in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, I was sometimes, yes. And we used to have what they called Anniversary - each year. Do they still have that sort of thing in churches in chapels? I never hear about it. They called it Anniversary, and it was - wha
t it was the anniversary of I just can't remember, but it was always about Easter time in the spring, and my mother always made us s- my sister and I - a lovely white silk dress you know, and a new hat trimmed with - flowers, and new gloves. We always had
 to be made up like a dog's dinner on Anniversary day. Mm. A lovely day that was. Had special - organ music and - all Easter flowers. Used to love it. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you know if there was any other club at the chapel organized for the older people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I don
't think older people ever met like they do today. No. They used to have committee meetings for the - people that - looked after the chapel you know. There was always a superintend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 e}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 nt and a - vice-superintend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
nt and - well, we didn't call them ushers I don
't know what we did call them, all the people used to meet to arrange everything you know. Then they used to run a slate club. Where you paid - your mothers and fathers always paid - sixpence or a shilling a week in case they died, to draw out - a few pou
nds. Every Friday I - used to go to the slate club to take the slate club, the money, and about a dozen other peoples cards you know, with ours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you say grace at home at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes, we did, yes. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who would say it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Probably my dad. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were you taught to say your prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you say them all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, we all used to get - you know, ready for bed together, yes, we all used to say them downstairs and then - go upstairs to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have family prayers with father taking them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, he was a Liberal. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Why do you think he was a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well - he was a one man business, and that affected hi
s outlook on lots of things. Because my mother was a Co-operative woman. Yes. And I suppose - if they'd have been a Labour party then probably she would have been Labour. She would have thought Labour, she wouldn't have definitely - you know, gone against
 
him, but I think they - were sort of more or less the same. But he was a staunch Liberal. Used to wear his colours and - you know, if anyone asked us we'd got to tell them that he was a Liberal. Mm. I think it was because there was something about free tr
a
de at that time, and - he believed in that, you see. Probably now he would be a Conservative because they believe in that don't they. Fighting for yourself and all that sort of thing you see. Politics have changed quite a lot. But really - you know, he wa
sn't - he wasn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 the sort of man that would have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  quarrel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 l}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
ed about it, now my husband's father was a Conservative and he used to go to the Conservative club, and he would - anybody that wasn't Conservative he jolly well let them know - what they was missing 
you know. My dad wasn't like that you know, he just sort of quietly - con - convinced us that he should be Liberal and we should be Liberal. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember he or your mother voting in a general election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes, they used to vote, yes. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember a particular one before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I don't, no. I remember all the bunting and the colours you know. Yellow and blue it used to be. Had to wear yellow and blue and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would father have done any campaigning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. Oh no he wouldn't have done anything like that. My husband used to. Mm, for the Labour party, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did your mother do anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. Oh no, she never had time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think that your father tried to persuade anybody say who worked for him to vote the same way as him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, I don't think so. No, he was - he was always a man that - his opinion was his own and he always used to say people think ad do what they like, you know, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did either of them take part in any political activities other than voting at election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, I don't think so, no. No. They would probably - I think I remember them going out to see - who had got in, and that sort of thing you know. The excitement at the night, yes, I think they'd - both would have done that you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 When they were not working which wasn't much of the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Wasn't very often, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did they spend their time when they weren't working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well mostly gardening. My mother used to take tea for all of us to the g
arden. We had a garden about a mile away from home. And she'd pack all the stuff up you know and - we used to have lovely picnics and at the garden. And we - and I used to - my dad used to give me a penny a day to tie his sweet peas up, 'cos you know how 
s
weet peas grow up long canes, and of course he used to chip every pea before Christmas and - set it in sand, and watch it in his greenhouse and then it used to go out, then on a certain day they'd got to be a certain height, then the flowers came. Each se
t of colours were the same, the mauves, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 picket}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
 edges, the creams, the pinks, and then he used to measure the stalks, then measure the flowers, to make sure the flowers was - the size of a matchbox across - the back of the flower got to be - I think matc
hboxes were much bigger than that - in - in our young days. And - the sho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
ts all have to be picked out, and I - it was my job to pick the shoots out, and tie them up as they went up the canes you know. Mm. And so we spent quite a lot of time at - in the ga
rden. And of course there was always the gooseberries to pinch and the rhubarb to pinch you know and the apples and - everything that we could always enjoys ourselves as well as do a bit of chores. And there was a well a most next door where we used to go
 and draw the water, to water, and he'd got a shed - mushrooms growing everywhere you know and that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Did your mother ever have any interests outside the home and garden, anything of her own, she had the hat business but did she have anything else apart from that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well - this aunt that she was always - they were always together, it was an older sister of hers, she was a Salvation Army person, and she used to do - she was one of the old pioneers that used to do - all this dirty work of looking afte
r girls that were in trouble, helping poor and dirty people, she used to do that and my mother used to help her. Yes. It was nothing to do with my mother, but she was always in the know and was going to help Aunt Flo you know. We used to have to make lace
 
and things to sell at the bazaars that they used to have. But on the other hand we was always invited to the - what they used to call - banquets, they used to have in those days. Huge banquets with food galore. Everything - all dressed up with corn and - 
and different things. And so of course we used to get a kick out of that, 'cos we - the boys used to be there you know and so - we'd do anything to get invitation to the banquet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 That would be run by the Salvation Ar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 y?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 By the Salvation Army. And
 my - my uncle - was - bandmaster and treasurer and my aunt was a singing - a songster you know, and they did - really did a lot of good work. Oh they did do a lot of good work. And my mother was always - her help. She used to go away sometimes to these h
omes visiting girls when they'd got girls there you know. Well we used to think they was mad 'cos in those days you used to think if a girl was in trouble she wasn't worth bothering about but you see then they used to think they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did mother ever go out just to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I don't think she ever did. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What time would father have got home from work in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He didn't used to come home before eight o'clock. They used to work in those days from eight to eight, and when
 I was fourteen I worked from eight 'til eight, for five shillings a week, and I - used to walk a mile to work, a mile home to lunch, dinner, hot dinner we used to have, a - a mile walk back, home at four to tea, back and work until eight. Yes. And Saturd
ay mornings if we worked - Saturday mornings from eight until one, we used to get an extra shillings. Yes, see how about that, ay?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did father ever go out in the evenings again after he came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, he used to have a boxing booth in his - in his 
- yard, and - several - men they were mostly one - one men business, a hairdresser - and - the football coach, and people like that, used to get together, and have these boxing - tournaments. Yes. Well nowadays people go and pay at a hall to see that sort
 
of thing, but in those days there weren't the halls and there weren't the - they didn't get up the big fights and things like they do now, and used to do it on their own, between themselves for their own amusement you know. He was a light weight, what the
y called a lightweight boxer. He was very interested in the football. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did he ever go out to a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, he never went to a pub, only when they went on outings - and called at a pub for a drink. They used to go to outings - like he'd go to the 
leather - well I used to go to the leather fairs in London with him. Mm. My mother and I. And - but they were big does, sort of national - does, where you saw all the foreign leathers, and the pick of the - beautiful stuff that was made you know. But -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Is that where he chose his leather from, where did he get his leather from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
He used to get his leather from Northampton. Mm. In - when my dad was young I don't think there are the bespoke makers now. I don't know anyone in Luton that does bespoke h
and - made shoes, but he used to - measure the - I was going to say patient, measure his customer, all up, and then he used to send all these measurements to Northampton, and they were made - he used to pick his samples of leather, he'd always got the lea
t
her - testing it and - you know - pulling it and - for the colour, got the colour got to be exact and everything, and he used to send away. Then it'd come back with what they called the upper made. That was all this part at the top without the bottom. And
 then he used to have the last, the wooden last, and then he'd - pull the leather over and the lining and put an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 interlinking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
 and then nail the two together, then he'd sew a band of leather that had been treated in water, and hammered and shaped, he'd stitch that. Then onto that he stitched the sole. And then he'd build the heel, and all like that you know, I watched him - stra
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 t from begin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ing to finish. Used to stitch, they used to put - he used to put - an awl in there and an awl in there then pull the tw
o out together. And - my granddad used to say to me when I used to watch my grandad doing it - he used to say, there, that's taken me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
quarters of an hour to do half of it. Now how long is it going to take me to do the second half? I used to say, well three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
quarters of an hour. He said, half an hour. I said, it can't, must be three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
quarters of an hour. Half an hour. And I wasn't crafty enough to know until after he'd told me that when they first start they have long wax - that they have to pull twice
 because of the length. And the second half it's getting shorter and shorter, so all they've got to do is this you see. And that's how they used to - a yes, it was yes, and of course - you think, well of course if one half takes - takes three}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 quarters the other would but of course - they got the second half done ever so much quicker.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did they used the wax for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 They used to have to wax the thread. Have a ball of wax in his hand and they used to have a leather thing over the hand and - t
hey used to keep waxing the thread all the time. But when he worked in London, when he worked in New Bond - when he had work from New Bond Street - I don't know what he used to use then but it was like yellow silk stuff. It was special - must have been sp
e
cial waxed thread, done yellow, and he used to have to cover every shoe with cotton - linen - before he started making it, so that actually he was covering and making a linen shoe, and then at the end he had to cut the linen away, which left the shoe - co
mpletely without a mark, finger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 mark on it. And then - he used to have to prick - the stitches, sixteen }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 stitches to the inch every inch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 , sixteen stitches to the inch, and he used to have to prick every one up, so they all stood like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How much would a pair of shoes like that cost?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well I think they used to cost somewhere between ten - seven to ten pounds to the customer. I think my dad used to get about two pounds for making a pair. There was a lot of work in them. Beautiful, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did he belong to any clubs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How about mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would she be seen in a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Father did the boxing, did he do any other kind of sport, would he be interested in racing or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I - yes, he was interested in everything. He used to do competitions and - things like that but not to participate in them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was he a betting man at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, he put - if he sent a coupon on - in that cost him a - sixpence or a shilling or whatever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 But he wouldn't bet on horses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I don't think so, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they belong to any other sort of savings club apart from this slate club that you told me about, any boot club or sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. I don't think so, I think my mother used to sort of just put a little bit by you know, if she was very - careful, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you get on with your brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Very well. No we all got on well together, we still do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have any one that you were particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well - I used to work with my oldest sister. When I was - from when I was fourteen - until we were married we worked together. And then we've always been friends ever since, still are, we still visit now and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 She is the one you were closest too then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I think so. Then the youngest one was a designer, and I was the drawer, so I used to draw her fashions that she wanted done,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120  and to help her stit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ch them. She'd pin them, and then she used to pay me to - to stitch them, and all like that, so r
eally - and my brother, we - my brother and I have always been great friends. Still - we still are. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 When you were a child who did you play with apart from your brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I had - a girlfriend that's - still my friend, yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Neighbours children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, neighbours children. We used to play with the three boys that lived next door, used to have great fun with them. Mm. And we used to have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 orse code on the walls, tapping - tapping - things out on the walls. Yes. And the 
- other side we still - well - they're dead now but - the children we - we was friends right until they went to Coventry to live. Still friends you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where were you allowed to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, if we went out to play it was only outside our own do
orstep. Or if our friends lived in the next street, or up the street, or down the street, we were allowed to go there but not to roam the streets, you know, we never - never - never had to be out roaming the street. You could go to your friends and come b
ack. Or you could take your friend home. Or you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would you play in the back yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, we used to play in the back yard. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you ever go to a park or anything to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Used to have a swing in the back - yes, we used to go to 
the park to play. Because I had an accident - always got me lace with me, taking me crocheting and in those days things weren't guarded like they are now, used to have a crochet hook, my mother used to put a cork on the end of it, so that you wouldn't hur
t
 yourself, but somehow or other we were playing in the park, there were boys and girls together and I stuck this thing, it went right through me finger, I had to go to the doctor's and have it taken out. And I did that twice I did that twice. Once right t
hrough there and it come out there and once through there and they - it couldn't come out 'cos of me nail. And both times my mother had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you fall on it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It must have been a very fine one was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well they are fine, they're very fine, I used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Tell me about the crocheting you used to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well used to do lots, I've - I've still got some. It's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was it very fine work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, some was, yes. All these things I crochet, and all these things I've embroid
ered you know. You know, form - these - all these, I embroider all these - a little dirty they are, we've got no water this week, I was going to wash these. We have no - we've got no water on now, and I made this, a twenty-one luncheon - set. Twenty-one l
u
ncheon set, I used to have a lovely oak table with a - waved carved edge. And I made this so that it went on the table you know with no cloth. Then the first time I had it on my husband said to me, what's this? So I said, well, I said, don't you like it? 
H
e said, give me a cloth any day. How would you like a man like that? Oh he used to love me lace but - oh, he said, give me a cloth any day. Mm. But they're discoloured these are, some of these are - these are over fifty years old. And I used to embroider 
a
ll these things meself here. Yes, I've drawn - done drawn thread work, you can see look it's hand done. Used to do - and I've given them away, I've given things like this away. Mm. Well - now I daresay but people don't want them. People don't want them. I
t
's very rare I - look how discoloured this one is. I did all this embroidery on here. And I did one with a - what they call a church window pattern, it was about as wide as that - it was a lover's knot, with the church window next, with a huge - corner, a
nd I asked someone once which one they would like out of what I've got, and they picked that one. So I said, well if you - if you really like it and you want it I - you can have it. I gave it - gave it to them. Mm. I used to do -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How old were you when you started doing that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh I shouldn't think I was above - I should think I was about twelve. We used to have - my mother used to have a nurse come to our house to tea, when my sister had scarlet fever and they took her to the fever hospital, my
 mother used to ask the nurse back to tea, and she often used to come, and she used to do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 macram\'e9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
 work and - what they called - oh I forget what it was, you had a - a hook and you laced the thing across, she taught me to do that and I did no end of that. Look how discoloured this one is, and this, this must be about fifty years old. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It must have taken you ages to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I'm as quick as lightning. When I start I can't stop until it's done. And then I don't tough it any more for months and months,
 don't have the time. These I done - when I wasn't well about five - four or five years ago I did dozens of these, for cake }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 doyleys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  you know. For putting on cakes and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You must have very good eyes, have you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Not now. No. I embroidered this and 
drawn all this - this - you know, I used to draw all these. I used to make duchess sets for the - thing and piano covers and - all sorts of things I've made in me time. And give - give away.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You must have inherited your father's skill with his hands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 With his hands, yes I think so, yes, must have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 All of you are pretty clever at doing things aren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. Mm. These, you know, I used to get a little bit of linen and go round and round, make up your patterns as you went along, all the
se, look you can tell how old they are. And these. You see, they're falling to pieces, look, you can tell how old they are. I've got a good one you could have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 That's a pretty little edging isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well we used to make it up, I used to make it
 up. Yes. Yes. And I've never used them, you know, they're no - no good for anything, do you want it? You can have it if you like because - I shall never use them, you can have this if you like. I don't think that's torn. Here you are then. It wasn't wash
i
ng, it's ever so - you know. Well I use all mine you see for putting little vases on because of - I mean there's only me and my boy now and I don't bother to - set tables all lah-di-dah with candles now. Look here's another one, look how - look how discol
o
ured that is. And I gave no end of these away and I used to sit and crochet - lace round handkerchiefs to give people. I thought this was - rather nice really, there was twenty-one pieces I made, six of one size, six of the other, six small ones for the s
ide plates, and then one or two quite big ones, you know. Twenty-one piece. But I don't think nobody's never seen 'em, they've never seen daylight. They'll do for a jumble sale when I'm gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Can you remember any of the games you used to play when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, we used to skip, we used to have pogo sticks, and we used to pay - play - we used to have a rope right across the road you know, one one side and one the other, and line up, one behind the other and - go through the rope, and then
 you'd skip - salt, mustard, vinegar, pepper, I suppose you've done all that sort of thing haven't you? Mm. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 But there was no traffic then presumably coming down the road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, only horses, there were only horses and carts. And - another thi
ng we used to do - was - the shoe polish tins, and the cocoa tins, my dad used to make a hole in the middle, put a bit of string and we used to - trundle them along wherever we went, 'cos in them days there were nothing else to do you see. You got no mone
y
 or no expensive toys. And we used to make - we was never without things. We used to make hot - hand warmers out of old tins, with a bit of - lighted rag in it. Yes. If our hands were cold you know. All sorts we - everybody done - well we did, I don't kno
w about everybody, we did everything for ourselves and everything we wanted we used to do, we never relied on anybody for anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did mother mind if you got dirty when you were playing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I always used - used to get into trouble because I u
sed to get dirty. My sister was always ever so clean, I was always ever so grubby. And yet I've been the one that's done the most washing, and the most particular, and my mother used to say to me, you'll wash your skin away, and you had a clean one on yes
t
erday, you're not having another one today. I would be clean but I'd always get dirty. And how I did I don't know and I do now. I bet if I put anything on any good and do something I - I've got a spot or something on it. But then I straight way wash it. A
nd I'm forever washing, 'cos I must have everything clean, and yet - I can't - my sister, she could - keep the same things on, and she didn't get dirty, she was - it was built in her to be clean you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased or did mother say there were certain children she didn't like you to play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No. No, we used to play - some - one girl I used to play with, she was so poor that she got no food, and I used to take her into our house, my mother used to give her - hot food at dinnertime. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of a family did she come from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh ever so poor, they used to live - well, quite a way from us but oh she was ever so poor, and they - I don't know why, whether the mother - didn't bother to feed them or 
whether they'd got no money, 'cos there was no - help in those days for anybody. If someone didn't help you who knew you, you had to go without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did the father work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I don't remember the father, I remember the mother, I don't remember the father
. And I remember the girl as well as anything, and - she used to say, oh I wish I'd got some dinner to go home to. And my mum used to say, bring her in, and she used to give her - hot soup or something hot you know. And - they used to send - always send m
e
 home with notes, had my father got any shoes or anything we didn't wear, that would do for so and so and so and so. Because he used to make them, but then - we only had about one or two pair a year. They were good. We had winter boots and summer shoes yo
u
 see. And I think my mother used to give them when we was finished with them, but - and we always had nice shoes, but - some of the people grew up and married and were well off, and they're far better off today than I am. You'd think they was the Queen of
 
England to see 'em about. I say good luck to people like that, you know. But - there were some poor people. And then I used to have a friend that lived - the other side of the town, and she used to come up to a music teacher that lived near us, every Mond
ay teatime I used to take her home to tea. And my mother used to have her tea all ready, and she used to give it as quick as lighting 'cos she'd got to be - out of school at - if it was four, for her music les}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 on about quarter or half past and - she used to have a hot tea and then I - every Monday, year in, year out that girl come to my house to tea.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did she do well with her music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I think so, yes. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you belong to any sort of youth organisations at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well not until after 
we left school, and then there was a war on you see. When I was fourteen the war was on, and they used to have the YMCA and the YWCA, and they used to have concerts then, I used to love them. Oh we used to love that. And some of the girls I worked with us
ed to go and sing you know up on the stage, they used to be - thrilled about that. Mm. I wasn't old enough you know. I think if I'd have been about three years older I'd have done the same you know. I was ever so shy at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 When you were at school did you have any other hobbies besides your crocheting and needlework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Painting, I used to do a lot of painting. I used to sit - my friend that - went into hospital last week, her and I were in the ex seven with nothing to do, we'd done every sume card in the school, and we'd got nothing to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Ex seven was a class was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Ex seven was the - top class when you left school, and there was just her and I, she was a bit younger than me, we'd finished everything in the school ready to leave, 
but you couldn't leave until your birthday - when you were fourteen. And I used to sit and paint the whole of the time, to put pictures up round the wall. Used to do comic pictures and - sprays of gooseberries, sprays of flowers, paint some of dad's sweet
 peas, paint still object, vases and - and cats and birds and all sorts of thing, I used to love it. Used to spend hours and hours and hours painting. They all used to go up round the board you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did mother and father like them, were they proud of them, did they think you were good at it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I don't think they ever knew I done it. No. 'Cos in them days there was no co-operation like there is now at school. You just took the child to school and if anything was wrong they'd come and see - about it you know. Otherwise - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I always had a cat. And my mum and dad always had a dog of some sort. I always had a cat of me own. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did the other children have pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I don't think so, no. I was very ver
y fond of animals. A friend of mine and I - if ever we saw an injured animal we always used to collect it up, and - and treat it and - and that, and if it died we used to make little coffins and bury them. You see, that was our life when we were young bec
ause our minds were on everything that was going on round you at the time. There was no planning or we'll go here or we'll go there, 'cos - there was nowhere to go in those days, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you collect anything for a hobby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I have collected
 different things - in me time, but then I'm inclined to give them away. I've had a lovely brass collection and got rid of them, when I was going to America. And - it wasn't because I wanted to give them away, because I really thought about making a pound
 or two on them, and I thought, I might make a pound or two of them, and the fellow came and he was so taken with all the brass I'd got he took them away and I never ever had a ha'penny for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you know where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He came from round
 Luton. But it was someone that my - son - worked with, and he was talking about us all going to America and - he asked him if we'd got anything to sell, and I'd got a wireless to sell and all this brass to get rid of you know. And he had the wireless and
 
the brass and he didn't - pay me a ha'penny on the night. And my son said to him the next day, he says, you know you didn't pay my mother for what you had. And he said, oh no, he said, but I've brought the money for the wireless, he said, and I'll have to
 
see about the brass, you know. And from that day to this I've never had a ha'penny for it. Never. I said I'd never collect any more, but bit by bit - people have brought me little things you know. My mother brought me this about - and she's been dead twen
t
y-five years. Wherever she went she always used to bring us some little thing you know. Mm. And my husband made this. This is solid brass, you feel the weight of it, it's a paperweight. And he made me some beautiful candlesticks and I even gave those away
 
and I wish I hadn't now, yes. Yes. That unscrews, that's solid brass, he used to be in the brass, yes. Mm. Mm. I don't part with that, although I don't stand me letters on - it keeps them up. I have such a lot of correspondence, I've got - so many things 
to attend to you know that I - if I put them out the way I forget about them now. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you ever go fishing, you went for walks didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, yes, I did used to go fishing with my brother, but I couldn't stand the fishing the - with the ho
oks in the mouths, I used to dream about it and worry about it and gave it up. Mm. I used to say, I'll come with you if you're not going fishing. And even to this day - he's got a car and he'll say, you know, want to come so and so? I say, not if you're g
oing fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes. Me and my - me and my - sister had a bicycle between us. We had to have a bike between us, so we used to ride the boys bikes, we always - I learned to ride on a boys bike, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you go far on them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh yes, used to go round the roads, me and my pal, and always remember running into a milkman, in those days milkmen used to push carts about, calling out. Penny a pint separated milk, tuppence a pint full cream. This is the price of it in these d
ays. And I always remember - I was going to turn a corner as this man was coming up the hill, and I went into his milk cart. Oh he swore at me, frightened me to death. But, yes, me and my sister, we had one bike between us. And she wasn't a lover of cycli
ng so I really had it more than she did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you take part in any sort of sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Not that I can remember of, no, there wasn't the sports for children then, we used to do a lot of drilling - and skipping and all sorts of things you know but there weren't the sports then as there are now, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 Did you ever go to a th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 eatre or a concert hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes. Yes. Used to go to the theatre regular. So did my mother and father, every Monday night - my father used to take my mother to the theatre. He used to love live plays and that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of things had they on in the theatre in Luton?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well they used to have - of course the plays in those days were lovely - sentimental type of plays you know. You might see a tear jerker on here now
 and again and say, oh, that's what the old folks used to see, well we did. But in those days we used to think that was very nice you know. And comedies too. We saw Gracie Fields when she was young. She came to Luton. Yes, and we always had - either a bal
cony seat or a seat in the pit, but when Gracie Fields come we had to go right up the top, frightened me to death, 'cos you couldn't get in. And that's some years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was there music hall there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, used to have music hall, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you go to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And pantomimes, we was always taken to the pantomimes, yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you go to the music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Music hall, yes. Yes. I've seen the music halls in Luton built, they were built - one or two of 'em were built when I was about twelve 
or thirteen and we seen them go up, from the foundation like that library over there's going up. We've taken part in them, I used to go to them when I was courting, we used to go to Saturday morning jewries. What they called jewries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
That was before films came out like they are now and picture houses. It was a little room in the Town Hall, they used to call them Jewries Pictures. And they used to flicker. And we always went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Why were they called Jewries Pictures?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Jewries, I don't know. I don't know, I don't know. And we were only kids, we used to go to these Juries, and it used to be three}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
pence and then when you came out they'd give you orange. Mm. Saturday mornings sometimes we used to go there. And then - the music hall
, right through my courting days we always went to music hall, and right until my husband died he always booked up for the - shows and the musical, we used to go to London and - everywhere to the shows, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have any pocket money when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, used to have penny a week off me dad. And I used to have a few coppers off me mum for helping her with her work. Then I used to take the neighbours hats to the factory, and do her washing up and clean all her cutlery, she used to give 
me a shilling a week, and I used to help the lady the other side do her hats. If she was in a hurry and I used to sit and help her do them. She'd sometimes give me a shilling. So we didn't do so bad, you know, no. Can always buy - I always used to like ni
c
e ribbon - on me hair, and things like that, and I always used to - have this money to buy things like that what I wanted you know, yes. Well - my mother always used to buy us ribbon. But I suppose I always wanted something a little bit better or somethin
g a little bit different you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you ever buy sweets with your pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, we used to buy sweets, yes. A lot of fruit we used to buy. Oranges and pears. And we use to live near - a people - some people that had an orchard, and you c
ould call in any day and any time for a ha'penny apple. And without a word of a lie it was as big as that, big as a baby's head. You could hardly get through it for a ha'penny, and they'd go and pick it off the tree, or if they had picked some you could h
a
ve your pick out of the - basket or whatever they'd got them in. For a ha'penny, yes. You'd pay about - a shilling for an apple like that today, and my mother used to buy those to bake, you know, she used - bake - bake them in the oven, with honey or - su
gar, lumps of sugar we used to put in the top. Lovely they were. I do now sometimes. I do mine like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did anyone outside the house help mother to look after her house, you told me about Annie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, Annie, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 She wasn't a relation was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you find her, was she a friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well her father used to work with - the same place that my father worked at - in London. He used to have - a different type of work sent down. You see, with this hand made - there was different types of work, 'cos some would do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4594632\charrsid14287120 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 s work that were heavy, well before my father went to work to London he used to make officers shoes in the first world war, officer field boots, and he'd have big field Marshall's come to be made for shoe
s and he used to do them, he'd do anybody's shoes, my dad would. But, when he worked in London he was on all the - light - dancing pumps, what they used to call dancing pumps, and walking shoes and evening shoes and all that sort of thing. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And Annies father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Annie's father - I don't know - remember what he used to do. I can see him now sitting doing it, and I - we used to go to their house because they had a little off licence. In those days they were little tiny - it was like an ordinary ho
use and the front room would have a little - bar counter across with a handle, and people used to go in with a jub, half a pint, and they used to keep this you see. Yes. And I suppose the mother - Annie's mother used to look after that. And the father use
d to do these shoes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 If mother was ill or stayed in bed for some reason or other how did you manage at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I mostly used to look after her. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 When you were too young to do that who would have helped?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well we used to have an aunt that was very good. She used to come, they used - our relatives were always up there, and my grandma.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember any of the younger children being born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I remember me youngest sister being born. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was she born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
We were all born at home in those days. You only had a doctor, my mother always had a good doctor, and a midwife that came in, you know, used to look after everything, and they used to be good - women, ever such god women. Yes -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you know what was going on or did it take you by surprise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well, I was always surprised. Yes, I was ever so surprised when my mother had - my youngest sister. And I always remember me brother, 'cos in those days they
 used to have all lovely lace drapes round the fireplace my mother used to, and she had a fire, I remember my brother - setting all these - muslin things alight while she was in bed with the baby. And that was - I think it was - I know - he was supposed t
o
 go to one of my aunts to stay for a week or two while she had the baby, because he was only about - two or three. And I was only - couldn't have been above - seven, could I, and he came home from her house right the way through the town and home, I don't
 
know if it was before he lit this - these curtains or not, but it was soon put out. My dad got all these things and put 'em in the fire and - got rid of 'em, yes, always remember that. And - we were all under ten when my youngest sister was born. Mm. So I
 wasn't very old was I?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You had relations living nearby didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, we'd got my mother had got - there was nine brothers and sisters of my mother's, and my grandfather lived in the next street, and I had an uncle live almost opposite, up a 
little bit, and - two aunts lived - with my granddad. We'd always got the aunts round. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You saw a lot of each other did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. Mm. All of us, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did father have some relations around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 They were his relations that I'm telling you
 about. That lived near. Mother's relations lived all over the place. One here and one there you know and they were always at home. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You're a very close family then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, we were, I think we were very close.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did your parents have special friends of their own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well, I don't think other than neighbours. My mother and father were very friendly with the neighbours and they used to come in sometimes - and - have a bit of supper, and I always remember 'em laughing and joking, that wa
s with the neighbours. And the women the other side was more - a woman that wanted to keep to herself, but my mother was always in there if she was ill or anything wrong with the children, they were ever such friends, but the one the other side was - what
 
you would call a card, her and her husband, you know, always ready for a laugh and - and - yes, and they often used to come in. And I always remember when she had her - little girl, this one that lives at Coventry now - I was about twelve, and I came home
 
to dinner one day and we'd got lovely pudding, my mum put it on the table and when we was all round the table she said, now I've got something to tell you. We said, ooh, what's that mum? Mrs Gander's got a little baby girl. I said, she couldn't have. 'Cou
r
se she couldn't, I said, I was in there yesterday. Clearing her basket, and then it come to me, I'd been clearing a baby's basket out. And doing things, I didn't know, and I was twelve. Hadn't got a clue. I was in there day in and day out. No, don't remem
ber ever - no, it was such a shock when my mum told me, I said, she couldn't have. And Mrs Gander laughed to the day she died about that. She said, I shall never forget your face, she said, when you come in and see my - my baby. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did mother have any friends of her own that weren't father's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I don't think so, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Or father have his own friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He had lots of friends through his work. Mm. Business people because you see he had the shop away from home, and business people 
used to go there and sit and talk to him, about one thing and another and he was always - chiropodists were all his customers, used to do all the feet, and keep the feet in good condition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Your father did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, always done all the - corns and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 calluses}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  and - everything, nails and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was that customary for a shoemaker to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, he always did that for a favour for his own customers. He wouldn't do it for anybody else. Unless it was anyone that he knew I suppose he would. He used to do ours. But all his own customers always had their - feet kept nice - by him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And you had friends invited into the house didn't you,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes, we'd always got people in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And they had eats and drinks did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were there any particular days or occasions when they came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well, we used to have the aunts one day and granddad always came Friday nights and - there was always - yes, there was always someone there on Sunday unless we were going to Harpenden. I think the
y used to arrange it you know. Shall you come to Harpenden or - or will you come up my place or - I'll come up - your place or something like that you know. 'Cos we used to have parties at all the aunts. Used to have lovely Christmas parties. They used to
 come to our house, we used to have a houseful of people, and my mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120  used to cook hot turkey, hot p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
lum puddings and stuff at night, ten o'clock at night. And then about two in the morning we'd take them all home, singing along all arm in arm. It was like
 the country where we used to live on the edge of the town, now it's a built up area - as bad as this part - this part. Yes. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did friends pop in and out casually as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And neighbours would be in and out would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 We
ll, not in the day a lot you know, people used to seem to be very busy. And - I think they would come in if they wanted to know anything or - arrange anything, otherwise, you know, there was no gossiping, my mother wouldn't gossip. No. And nor would my gr
a
ndmother. When I was married my mother - my grandmother said, I should give you the same advice as I've given all my children, don't gossip. Don't tell people your business. Yes, my grandmother did. And she'd got some friends. Heaps of friends. Rich peopl
e used to take her things and - give her things, they loved her, I don't know why, but she was lovely - lovely old woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 But she wouldn't idle gossip?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You said that you made your own amusements in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 When you got together at parties what sort of things did you do to amuse yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well we used to have sing-songs round the piano galore. We used to have the fire irons for bands, we used to have any tin - for a drum, and we used to have bazookas, paper with combs if we couldn't make a noise any other way. Anything for fun. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Game, yes, we used to have games. Used to be - cards, and snaps and - my dad and I always had billiards, they always had a billiard table. Yes. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where would that be kept?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well they used - don't know - even the doctor and his wife used to come and play billiards with us. Yes, right until my mother died she used to have people in, billiard night and - people used to come you know, game of billiards and a supper.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would the billiard table be in the front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I - I think they used to prop it up somewhere and then put it on the dining table. Yes. There was always billiards and - my dad used to have - he used to experiment with thi
ngs. He used to have a steam engine, made of lovely brass, it was about as big as this, now today I bet it'd be worth a packet, I daresay he bought he it for about five bob, and he used to put methylated spirits in it, and we all used to sit round the tab
l
e thrilled to bits watching him - when he got it going and it used to chug-chug-chug-chug-chug-ghug-chug around like this, and the steam used to come out and we used to think that was lovely. Well of course in them days engines were something new and - an
d - if it's still in circulation now, it could have been picked up at a junk shop for a few bob and I'll bet it is now worth something, but - times and times he's had the whole engine out and we've - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He was a man of many interests wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I've thought of what I did the first day I started school. Yes. The first day. The first day. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Tell me about the things you've written down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh I've just scrawled 'em down as I thought of them. We used to make our own
 sweets and chocolate - out of cocoa butter and - yes, stuff like that. Our own toffee we always used to make. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How about the games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 The games, yes -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Writing secret letters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, oh yes. We used to - used to write to our friends,
 or if it was to a boyfriend and we wanted 'em passed on - we used to fold them in like tht - like that you see, and then write, and I bet if you gave them to anyone to take, and they'd been opened they wouldn't get it back together again right you see. S
o you'd know, yes. And then - I used to write mirror writing, so that they had to put it up to the mirror to read a letter. Used to do that like lightning. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Could you do it now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I expect so, I don't know, I've never tried for years. Oh dear, where's me pen I'll answer you now, I'll behave.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Many people at that time divided society into different social classes or groups. Did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another in your childhood? Can you tell me what the different ones were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well - mostly - as far as I recollect and I suppose it's hearing my mother and father talk were - the council}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ors were always the landowners. They used to live in the big houses, and buy up all the land. And I used to hear my father say - 
sometimes, you know, they'll make a packet when they sell this and when they sell that, which they did after - years afterwards, as the town spread. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were they at the top of the list as it were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes, and they were always the people tha
t you sort of bowed down to, you know, and - their children was always - either private school, there weren't the high schools or the education - not - universities and things like that like there is now. Everyone used to go to school until they were four
teen, and if they took an examination and passed the - labour before, anytime after eleven, my brother left school at thirteen, passed the labour with honours and - was out to work, you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You said the landowners were the top of the scale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. Well they were those -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who would have come next?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well - I should think the shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 owners. The shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
owners. Which were very nice people, and very - very friendly and very nice and helpful. The shopkeepers used to be - much more helpful in thos
e days than they are now, much more obliging you know, and understanding. Because it was over the counter, you and - him, you know, not - a young girl walk up that doesn't know anything about it, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who would have been next down do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 W
ell - I think the manufacturers. The manufacturers were just on the up and up in my young days. You know. From - my mother's - when - when they did it when they were young, and my grandmother, they all used to do it in the house, you know, by candlelight 
o
r lamplight, they all used to sit and twist the plait you know, and my mother used to have an old mill, what they called a mill on the door, and it was my job to put this plait through the mill, so that the head always stood up, and you've ever - have you
 
ever seen when you've bought a hat, how it's got ridges - ridges, well that's all - that all used to be milled, I don't think they do it these days. Milled so that - half the plait was flat and half stood up in a ridge, and the ridge was on the outside as
 
they worked it, so that the ridge went round and round, and it had to be perfect you know. And - I don't think they do anything like that now. And the manufacturers after my mother's time as they got - more - well, I suppose you could call them bit larger
 
factories, they were all behind the houses, until several opened in the town, you know, those that got on more than the others. And - very nice people they were, the people I worked for were very nice. They were mostly local preachers at the churches and 
chapels. So if you went to anything at the church and chapel they was always there. And you was always honoured if you was in the company and - and - they always treated us very well you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where would you say you came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I should call us middle class. Middle class, because we were quite ordinary people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were you on the same level as these manufacturers you've been talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, not in the money}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 wise. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 A bit below that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes. Far below that. My father was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
esloke shoemaker, and he worked on his own and he worked very hard and beautiful work, but no money attached to it in those days. And my mother used to work - well the work used to pick up about November, and she'd have a machine and work until about Eas
ter or Whitsun, so did I when I was married, after I was - got children, used to do it at home like that, what they call seasonable work. Mm. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who would come underneath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well then underneath us there were very poor people. Very poor people, but we were all friendly together. I was - at school you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did the poor people do for a living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well they were either in the hat trade, whether they were - whether they had drunken fathers or illiterate lazy mothers, I wouldn'
t remember that much. I can see them in me mind's eye, children - some of them they used to have hardly any shoes on their feet, hardly any clothes and hardly anything to eat. Never seemed to do anything or go anywhere or - have anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember seeing drunken}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh yes. And snuff. People used to take snuff in those days. The old girls used to curl up in your - right of way, you know, all night. Yes, and we had a friend that was a manufacturer, he was a charming man, and this was his 
wife. And my father used to make her shoes, he - when she was sober. He used to say, I want you to make - I forget her name now, so and so a pair of shoes. He'd have a pair of shoes made for her, beautiful costume or anything. And she}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 d be all right for tw
o or three weeks, then you'd find her laying around again. Used to be that sort of women - about. Yes. I don't think she was a prostitute or anything like that - drink and snuff, and they used to say, dirty old cat, you know, they used to say. But looking
 
back I suppose really they were ill, mentally - sick or something you know. And they had a son, always remember they had one son, and he was just the same. His shoulders, he used to roll about, and he's got a charming family and I'm very friendly with his
 family now. And they've got big homes, far better off than I am. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Is he still around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, the - the old people are dead. But - the woman - I don't know if she died or if she went into a home, and he took a housekeeper, she was a London pers
on that was a court dressmaker, and she was more in line with his way of thinking. And he'd had a very sad life with his wife and - she was charming and she used to keep these lovely - grey dogs, what do they call them now - those with the lovely round he
a
ds, she used to have two or three, and - we were very friendly with those 'cos they used to have a garden near us you know. She was a charming woman. But as she got older she got - shabby and - she used to come to see me when she was eighty-two, and I use
d to have to stitch buttons on for her, take pints out - I'm getting on that way, I hope I'll never get like it. She was as smart as I was when she was young, used to be a beautiful dressmaker. Amazing, see when the brain goes you know, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No. No. The only time we were ever told not to go with people, if they were dirty. Some people really dirty and lousy, you know, used to be that type about i
n those days. And my mother always used to say, don't - don't bring them in my house and don't go in their houses whatever you do. But I think we used to. I think I used to, it didn't seem to matter to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How about the people who were above you in social standing, were you taught to curtsey to them or your brother to touch his cap?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No. Oh yes, everybody touched their caps in those days. Yes. And my husband used to call his boss sir. Yes. And - all - several people I've known him call sir. But as he got older - he wouldn't do it. He turned. And he used -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 But in your childhood everybody did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 In my childhood everybody did, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did anybody call your mother and father sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Never remember, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who were the most important - people in the town, who was considered the most important person in the town, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well - most important - well - I should think the Mayor was in those days, more so than now. The Mayor's are pretty friendly, they come round t
o the old peoples - does and all that, I don't think they would have done that in those days, they were up - above that you know. Mm. But I've worked for a mayor, and he was very very nice to work for. Fair, and - good, you know, but never to - never to r
e
ally have much to say, but I think I must have been a bit cheeky when I got in me teens, because I've worked for people that have been like that, and I've been carrying on a nice old lark, dressing up and - putting orange peel for false teeth and differen
t
 things you know, larking about, and the bosses have come in and I've thought to myself, oh my goodness, I'm in for it now, and they've said, tut, tut, tut, you're a one, you know, and - just palmed it off, yes. And in later years - particularly a German 
I
'm thinking about that - when they were purged out of Germany they came here, and I worked for them oh ever so many years. And I used to do all the sketching for them, and when the designer used to go to Paris she used to come home with things she'd seen,
 
and used to ask me if I could do them. I used to have to try them out, work in - ribbon upside down in a machine so that - when - when the machining was turned the other way, all the ribbon stood up, in layers you know. I did some beautiful hats like - I'
ve never seen them. She used to say that she was going to buy one, but she never did. Whether she couldn't afford or not, I expect she used to think, oh - Glad'll know what I mean and do it you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You just had them described to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, just - described, yes. They used to make an awful lot of money of those. 'Cos they were models you see. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You say the mayor was the most important man in the town?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, he was. I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of man would he have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He was a very upright slim built man with beautiful white hair and lovely - kind eyes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did he do for a living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He'd got a hat manufacturing place. Yes. Hat manufacturing. In fact -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did he have a lot of work to do in the town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, I think ev
eryone looked up to them you know. I think they looked up to them like we look up to Prince Philip, that type of thing. They were somebody. Yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who would have been on a level with the shopkeepers, friends of the shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I should think the teachers. Teachers were very important when we were young. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How about clergymen, where would they have come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well the clergymen were too. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were they above teachers and shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, clergymen were, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would they have associated with hat manufacturing people and people like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh yes, yes, they were - yes, they used to get together a lot - that type of people at the chapels and churches in those days, they used to meet and - of - course the
y all had - and I've got a picture, I'll show you soon, of my grandfather, they all had frock tail coats you know, cut away at the front with the - frock tail coats and that, and - oh everybody used to go to church and chapel dressed up to the nines. Us k
ids had to be - clean and tidy and - not a h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ir out of place and our gloves on and - look round your - your }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 eels and everything, make sure we were all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where do you think farmers came in this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Farmers, well - we'd got a friend that was a f
armer round Luton, and - he's very well known, his - he's died now but his wife is a - magistrate. And - my father always did his shoe work, and they were very friendly with my family. They were landowners, they owned acres and acres and acres of land. An
d
 they used to say to my father when we were young, you can come gleaning for your chickens, we used to go gleaning - all round his corn fields. He used to give my father the tip when they'd - had the cutters and the - I don't know what you call them - cut
t
ing the corn down, then we used to go gleaning. We used to get sacks and sacks and sacks of corn - for our chickens. And he used to always say to my dad, if anyone's - you know, messing around, tell them they've got no right to be there, but we always did
.
 Yes. And that was very nice, 'cos there was blackberries and - everything, we used to - go out, my mother used to pack up bottles of tea, bottles of lemonade, and we used to go - you know, it was near - between - he owned the ground from - Round Green, d
o
 you know where Round Green is? From Round Green nearly to Hitchin. On both sides of the road. And now they're selling off - for the building, it's absolutely taken - right to Stratleigh, I think his address is Stratleigh. I've never been to the house. No
w my mother used to knit all her children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
s socks and do things like that for them. Yes. And my father used to do all the shoe work and - leather repa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
ring that - wanted doing, you know, and for the doctor. A pair of gloves they'd bring in you know and - my
 father had the job to - to do them. I think that's how it was he made such a lot of friends. Because I think he done lots and lots of things like that for nothing. Yes. But - he always - this Mr Manning and Mrs Manning always took them a turkey at Christ
mas. And he'd come home with a hare any old time. That Mr Manning came in the shop. And he'd sit and talk to my dad just as though they were equal, well they were of course. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 They must be nice people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, he was - he was a - he was one of the biggest farmers round here, still is. His wife owns the ground now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would you say there was any difference between the people who went to the church and those who went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 The people that went to the church, to the churches, I think w
ere more hikey than the people that went to the chapel. Not so friendly. Have you ever heard - heard that. Hikey. Hikey is uppish, you know. Yes, oh they're uppish, you know, hickey used to call it. And - at church there was always a reverent atmosphere -
 
of silence and reverence that there wasn't in the chapels, in the chapels you could always have a giggle, and we used to have great fun at the chapel I went to. But when I - when we picked up with boys, when we were older, we left chapel and went to churc
h
. And of course we - I suppose we became sort of - bit pious looking like they did. Yes, we used to go and - go to the church and go to all the organ recitals and things. Don't know whether it was the church or the boys that were the attractions. But they
 were nice boys anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Where you lived did all the people in the lower classes have the same standard of living or do you think among them there were different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, there were, we lived in a road - where from our house - and the neighbo
urs down - upwards to the next turning of the street, were all people that were higher class than us. But from about two doors below us, down the road, were scruffs. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Can you describe to me a family of both sorts,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well - one family in partic
ular I'm thinking of was the person that we bought our house off of when I was thirteen, my father bought - he was the manager - of the - biggest dye works in Luton. The dye works, that died all the hats, all the plaits, and he was the manager. Well he li
v
ed in a house, I shouldn't think it was above a couple of bob a week more than ours. And at that time ours was only six bob. And they lived there until their two children grew up, and they were always, clean, tidy, nice people you know that - we used to p
lay with the children. And then they moved, when we bought their house and went in Talbot Road they moved to a big house, a big corner house in the Dunstable Road. And of course they wen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 
t up and up. But we still visit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ed because my dad always had their work. So we always used to go to their house. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Can you remember a family who lived down the scruffy end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I still meet with - some of them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How would they have lived that was different from the way you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, I think they
 had larger families. And weren't so competent in some way. You know. And perhaps the women didn't work. Some didn't, couldn't or wouldn't work. And so I know my mother's earnings made a lot of difference to our house, because the first week my mother - w
o
uld earn a good week's money she'd go out and buy enough material to make my sister and I a dress. The next week she'd go out and buy material for - petticoats, we used to have lovely lace camisoles she used to crochet - all the tops, and the bottoms make
 of white lawn. Well now people wear bras instead of them. But it was always }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 camisoles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
. Yes, beautiful things they were. And - go on, you say - and these sort of people never seemed to wear those sort of things. So whether my mother was very - fussy and par
ticular, or whether they - didn't know or didn't care, but there was just that difference, you know, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Do you think there was a difference in the same sort of area as you were and the same sort of people roughly, do you think there was a difference between craftsmen and labourers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, no, we had - there was my father was a - was a - a specialist in his work, the man next door - up and the man next door down were both on the railway. And Railway in those days was supposed to be good jobs. They were supposed to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would you have thought they were labouring people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well more so than my dad, in a way. And probably in their dress and little outlooks. But - their money I think was pretty good you know. Used to reckon that they'd got good
 jobs on the railway. Because I always remember one side, the man paid two or three shillings a week for a pension. And when he retired, this was after I got married, years afterwards, he retired and he lived quite comfortably, and - he used to say that t
h
is other man grumbled because he hadn't got enough to live on, but he wouldn't pay the pension. In those days people had the choice. There weren't the unions. But people had a choice. You either saved a little and done well, or you spent it or didn't both
er to pay for things and you - you went sort of just down a little bit. Yes.
