Well, there used to be good seasons and bad seasons. People in businesses in straw hat businesses - probably would make - quite a lot of money - over and above a weekly wage - in a season, then they'd have what they call a bad season. The stuff
 either wasn't - fashionable enough, or wasn't sold - enough, or they hadn't got a decent - what they did call them now, travel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 er. Trave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
lers used to go out with the hats - to take - sales orders, and if they didn't get a good trave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ler, they were down. T
hey'd pay anything for a good traveller. Yes. Yes. And - and then if they had a bad season they were down and out. But I think they used to go to the pawn shops in those days. There used to be a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 paw}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 n shop with three golden - things over, and I don't think 
my other - my mother ever went in a pawn shop in her life, she was far above that. But there used to be people round that I do know used to go with a - big bundle on Monday mornings, and queue up, like a queue at the pictures, to take a bob or two for per
h
aps all their clothes. And then at the end of the week when they drawed some money, if they drawed any, they'd go and get it out and they had to pay this man an interest. If he gave them two shillings they'd have to pay two and six, to get them back. And 
people like that were always in debt. And I see people today about that used to do that week in and week out. I meet women now. Day in and day out was at the pawn shop. It was just the habit and their way of living, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember anybody being described as a real gentleman or a real lady? And what do you think that meant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well - this now that I'm telling you about, his name was Mr Warren, I think they called him a perfect gentleman, I think I've heard people say you know, he's a perfect ge
ntleman, they'd say that about that type of man then. Now they wouldn't. No. Oh no. No. The - the peoples outlook on people have changed. A man -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
 you think a real lady would have been in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well - I really can't say. Because peop
le I think that we thought in our young days were ladies - after - in after years you found out they were bitches, you know. Yes. Not altogether truthful, not honest, and horrible ways. And some of them when you were young, you did look up to them and thi
nk they were somebody. But now looking back they were bitches. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of women would they have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well they were - they were mostly - people like foreladies that were over lots of girls. Now I was a forelady over a lot of girls, b
ut it learn - taught me a lesson, I was never like that. I used to be friendly with all the women, and when the first world war was on they used to bring - sausages to me to take home for my mother, and anything they could get - they'd bring to me. And th
e
 people used to visit me after I was married, and look back on the days - yes, and - some of them that - well they lived to be quite old and I've met them over the years, have always looked back and said, didn't we have some fun. Yes. I think I must have 
b
een - yes, I think I - yes, well, I'm thinking of one forelady in where we first worked, and she used to - us - new ones, a friend and - and I, when we first went when we were fourteen - she used to let us run errands for her, and of course she ruled the 
r
oom and the place with a rod of iron. We used to look up to her because she'd got beautiful auburn hair, and she was always - what you might say, you might think they'd call her a lady, and - she'd come in one day and she'd say to my older sister - I don'
t
 know if I ought to say this on the tape. Anything. Yes. You're sure? Does your - does your young sister see her periods? So my sister said, yes. And she said, well, she said, there's been - some towels found - tucked somewhere, and she said, we wondered 
i
f it was one of the kids. Me, or this other girl. But she was a very nice girl. And my sister said, no - she - she would never do a thing like that. Well when my sister told me of course I'm the worrying sort, I thought, my goodness, I hope they don't thi
n
k it was me. I used to think, if they do - if she tells somebody and they think it's me, you know, really worried me, and do you know, a girl that worked on the bench at the end, she come up to me and my sister and she whispered, she said, they're hers, t
h
ey're hers, I made them on my machine, and she changed in the toilet and put these there and they was hers. And this girl come and told us. You see. And - nobody dare say anything. Then she came - it must have been a year or two after that, she came in an
d
 said she had lost her purse, had anyone seen her purse? Well we used to go shopping, and of course - us kids, the youngest ones that used to do her shopping thought, oh dear, you know, whatever's become of her purse, she must have laid it somewhere, hope
 
she don't think we've got it or had it. And do you know that purse was found down the toilet. She had pretended - and put this purse down the toilet and she bought it in wet and showed everybody. And that's the sort of thing she used to do. Mm. She was a 
bitch. She was a bitch. And to this day my sister and I - my sister sat in here the other week and she said, oh - do you remember old Ginny Large, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What was her name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Ginny. Yes. But she'd got a lovely home, she used to have us to her h
ome you know. Yes. I think it was more of a show off, 'cos all her carpets had got white linen covers over them. Mm. Didn't have to walk on the carpet. Or the stair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 carpet had got white linen up the middle you know, and she'd got a nice husband, she's dead
 now but - you know, we used to think she was ever so good, because of her appearance and - she always used to go for holidays when we didn't you know and all that. But oh she was - it's true when I say she was a bitch. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you ever remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you think of him, was he friend or was he a sort of ogre that your mother threatened you with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, no, we were never threatened, and I don't think they used to talk to 
us much but I do remember once - when we - I was only about fifteen - and - I'm not sure if it was the bombs - or if it was the weather, if it was the blizzard, I can't remember which, but there was a bad blizzard and then there was bombing one night - ea
rly in 14 war, and as we came - we used to go home on the tram which was a three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
ha'penny tram ride, from the top of King Street to Round Green, home. But when the trams didn't run I think - I don't know if it was the blizzard of the bomb, we had to walk - 
along a road and right up the hill home, and as we were struggling along - I still can't remember if it was the blizzard or the bomb, the policeman said, where are you going? And we said, we've got to get to Talbot Road. And he said, well come along there
, he said, come this way, and go along here and up the road, and he walked a little way, we were a bit scared, wondered if he ought to walk with us. That's all I remember of a policeman when I was young. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you ever get the impression that he was 
generally liked by people or was he tough on some people do you remember, or the police in general, not that particular one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, I don't remember when I was very young but I remember when I was - in my early teens, seeing - two policemen man handle
 a young man, and bundle him into a van, and after he got in the van, they must have hit him with a truncheon or something, he screamed, and it worried me for months. And I hated policemen for a long while after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you know what he'd done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No. Probably he'd done something awful. But I never forgot that and I thought a dreadful policeman doing - things like that. And I can see it now, the van. Up a little side street and they bundled him in, shut the door, one policeman went in and it was af
ter the door was shut that this man screamed. And - but now - I find with my children that police have been a big help to both of them. And my oldest son's forty-five, he - he always - respected the police, and my little one does. They talk to him, and - 
yes, more friendly, ever so much more friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You owned your second house didn't you, did you own your first house or was it rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 The first house after I was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh no, the first house was rented.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you ever see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh yes, he used to call every Monday, and he owned the baker, he was the baker. He used to own a bakers shop and have a little horse and cart and they used to go out - men with the bred and the - stuff all over the place, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you feel about him, did you like him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well he was - I think he was pretty decent. And he had a daughter - that we knew quite well over the years, he left her an awful lot of money. Yes. But always remember my mot
her saying - he wouldn't do something when the drains - something went wrong with the drains, and I think that's why they moved. Everything had to be right for my mum and dad, you know. And I think as soon as they could - they got their own house you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember feeling that your parents were struggling to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did you think about it at the time, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 We used to give them all our money, I used to give them all my money. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think it made a difference if father was ill, if he couldn't do his work you'd have no money coming in would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I never remember my father being at home ill, never in his life, no. He lived to be eighty-four, and the last two years - before he died he 
did have a lot of trouble, but he never ever told anyone, only me. He used to come and sit in my house, and he used to keep going to the toilet and of course - I as I should do, it's like me to be like this - I said to him, dad, is there anything wrong? A
n
d he said, oh nothing to worry about, it's just that I have difficulty going. But of course I probed until I found out - that he was bleeding and all that. He'd been living with my sister ever since my mother died, she never knew a thing about it. And he 
wouldn't tell her, he said to me, don't tell Beattie, he was so afraid that he was going to be - troublesome to someone. Mm. He - I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember any help from any sort of charity help your parents ever needed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. Oh no. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do
 you remember if there was anyone in the district who the neighbours disapproved of really very strongly so that they showed it in any way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I remember one woman that used to - spend all her time - at the bottom of her passage of her house - tal
king and finding out things. And when my - I think it was when my youngest sister was born, my father was going to work and she said - has she got them? Has she got them? My mother was expecting my sister. So my father said, twins. Yes. Oh, then you know,
 everybody in the street - we've got twins. I shall never forget my father laughing about that. He wasn't mean but he was so cross you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you remember if anybody was ever forced to leave because of local disapproval? People apparently used 
to make something called rough music?
