\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How old were you when you first went to school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I don't remember if I was three or five, I think I was three. And my friend that I used to play with that lived over the road, we both started the same day, she was a little older than me, and - she cried because they wou
ldn't let her sit with me. And the first thing we had to do was, they gave us all a tinned mince pie, tin, and a piece of blue serge, you don't know what serge is do you? Do you? It's a material that's - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 coarsely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  woven, yes, yes. And they used to give us t
his and we had to pull - this way and that way until it was all the pieces in the mince pie tin tidy. That was the first thing I ever did when I went to school, and I remember that - as plain as anything. And I remember my friend crying because she couldn
't sit next to me. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And you think you were three?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I think I was three. I think we started at three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you go the whole day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I think so, it was only just the bottom of the street where we lived, yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What time in the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Nine I think. Home at twelve. Back about half past one or quarter to two. And home just before four. Mm. 'Cos always remember running up the street, I was ever so tiny, when me first tooth dropped out, and I walked all the way bac
k to try and find it. And I believe I found it and they said if I slept on it me mother was going to give me sixpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of a school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Very nice school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember if it was a church school or a board school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, it
 was a - no - no - there was a church school quite close to us but we didn't go there. We always used to thing the poor children went there funnily enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What was your school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It was a - it was a secondary school after - I left, but it was a very good school with very good school record.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was it a private school when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It was a board school then do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, not a board school, no it was a day school. We had schoolmistress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Board school doesn't mean that it was a boarding school, it was run by a school board of governors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh yes, because my - second cousin was the Educational Officer. My mother's cousin - used to come round with the papers - in his hand and of course I used to sit up and - yes, oh yes, I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Was it mixed, boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No. No, we had separate - all the girls - in one part and the boys just round. But the playground was - just a little wall dividing, you know, you could always talk to the boys over the playground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And you walked if it was so near?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How long did it take you to get there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh, about two or three minutes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh my sister and I used to go together and I think - and my frien
d that - you know, we were friends for years, there were two or three of us always together. You know, used to keep together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You had your midday meal at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, always had a midday meal home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember what you thought of school when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I loved it. Mm. Loved it, loved it always, yes. Right the way through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did you feel about the teachers, can you remember that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I liked the teachers because my dad used to do - make - three parts of the teachers
 shoes, and their parents, they were always good friends with the teachers. They used to take us for walks, a few of us - sometimes you know, botany classes, we used to take books and pencils and - then if you found anything nice, I used to draw it and al
l like that you know, always - always interesting for me. Then we used to have singing, I join - I joined the school choir. Mm. We used to have - you know we used to sing the old Cherry Ripe and all those - sort of - mm. Used to love that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember if they insisted on certain things as being important like manners and tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes. Oh yes. Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh punctuality. I remember a girl - friend of mine, I've seen her up until this last two or three years, and 
I never see her - ever in my life but what I've thought back to how they caned her, because she was always a few minutes late, and she'd got an invalid mother, she's had the same things her mother had the matter with her that I've had since I've been olde
r
, I didn't know it when we were at school, and she used to have to do the shopping and help her mother before she came to school. Every morning when she come to school she got the cane. And I used to go home and worry about that girls hands. And I worried
 - even up to she - when she was married, and when I've seen her in later years. I've never forgotten it. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they mind about the way you spoke at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes. I used to read 'cos they used to say I was a good - speaker. Used to be me, a
nd - two other girls used to have to sit up - high, on a - stool in front of the class and read to the class. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 If you did something that the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh they'd give you a jolly good smack. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And they used to cane girls as well as boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What other sort of things would they punish you for apart from lateness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well - I remember one teacher, my father always made her shoes, and we always got on very well together - but - after she was m
arried, whether us girls took the mickey out of her - because - we always used to call her Miss Horton, no, Miss - Nelson. Miss Nelson this and Miss Nelson the other. Well then she got married. And when she was married she asked me to crochet all the lace
 
for her curtains. And I crocheted all the lace, about that width, six to eight inches, for short curtains, and whipped all the lawn on, whipped it, how - do you know how to do whipping? Whipped it on, for all her windows. I did all that when I was married
,
 and you'd take that as being good friends wouldn't you? Well my father used to send her bunches of sweet peas, as a favour, and I used to have to take sweet peas to school to give one to each girl, the teacher used to give one to each girl to draw or pai
n
t. Well of course, knowing the beauty of the sweet peas I used to want to paint the best, you know, and I always remember once something I'd done, I think we called her Mrs Horton or - something, and she - oh I can see her face coming up red now, and she 
said, don't call me that in school. We're supposed to call her by her single name you see. Whether she took }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 umbrage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
 over that, but she gave me - an old sweet pea where the bottom one had fell off, and oh I was upset about it, I told my dad, I said, I'll nev
er take any more flowers to school, I was upset about that. Mm. She was really a nice person but - I think she got in a temper over something. I think - I don't know whether it was me or another girl - said something about Mrs Horton, I can -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Who was your favourite teacher then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well - she was a lady called Miss Impey, and she was ever such a lovely person. She used to tell us - what she wore to keep her slim. And in those days you didn't discuss things like that but she did. And she told us, sh
e said, don't ever wear these hard corsets like your mother's wear. Wear an elastic band. Well we couldn't understand how it was that she'd got such a lovely figure and she only wore an elastic band. But of course we all had corsets which we were supposed
 to have to keep us upright and straight backed and all that sort of thing. But now - I only wear things like that and I think about - all those years ago, if only we'd have been advised -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 She must have been a bit in advance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes, she was ever so sweet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they ask what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, wanted to know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I don't think they did, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Or meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I think they came down to take us when we first went. Or if we weren't well they'd come down and explain things. But there weren't the meetings and the associations. Not like there is now, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Father used to know some of the teachers through the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, he knew, so he always got to know everything that was going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did the other children at your school come from the same sort of home as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mostly. Almost every one in the district of about - eight or nine streets al
l went to - the same school as I did. Mm. There was manufacturers daughters, posh people, one woman - used to dye her girls hair then which was an unheard of thing. She used to come to school with auburn hair, and I still see that girl to this day, she wa
s - always dressed nice. H}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
ir actually done auburn. And that - this must be - sixty - three or four years ago, so what her mother used I don't know. Nobody else ever - ever thought of anything like that. We used to think she was ever so posh you know, 'cos 
she used to come - her hair'd be - well like ours is when it wants washing, like mine is now, you know a bit mousey looking, and then she'd come with it all done lovely and it used to look beautiful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes. They'd have - had their favourites. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of children would have been their favourites?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well the - the girls that were nice looking I think you know. My friend, one of my friends was ever su
ch a lovely looking girl. And she always seemed favoured in every way. And she's been favoured all her life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you remember if there were any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, there weren't. We used to go - two or three friends, and there was 
always one - that was spiteful, you know. But they all grew up lovely people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would there be one that was perhaps left out a bit?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. They were mostly if they were a little bit backward. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It didn't have anything to do with whether they were poor or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Nobody ever seemed to talk to them, they were just ignored you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 The backward ones you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. A little bit backward. I think they all grew up to be married, but they were all a little bit - we used to wonder - why
 they didn't jump around like we did and - answer up quick and - and do things you know, didn't understand, not when we was young. Didn't understand it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you go on to another school after that one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No. Went to that one right until we left. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How old were you when you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I was - nearly fourteen, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would you have stayed longer if you had had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No, I wanted to go to work. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have any part time education afterwards, any evening classes or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well not officially, we used to go - we got a boyfriend, my - this nice looking girl I'm telling you about, her and I used to go to a fellow's office and he used to teach us to type, and all that sort of thing, we always wanted to 
- to know the things, but there weren't the classed in those days to go to. And - he was a solicitor's clerk and he had a - must have had a better education than as, I don't remember what kind of education he had because we were only about sixteen and he 
w
as only about eighteen, and we lived near each other for years after we were married. And he married one of our old school friends, that used to be with us at school, and - we were ever such friends, but when my friend and I were young, we used to go to h
i
s off - office, and he was the first one ever to teach us to smoke. And in those days - so you can see we got a little bit of devil in us, it - you know, must have had, because we were never allowed to smoke at home. And - they were scented cigarettes, al
ways remember, they called them white lily. Mm. So we used to do our typing, and - get on with that and then have a white lily, and he'd take us home. It was all - ever so innocent in them days, we thought it was lovely, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No. No, not really. No. I like to know - I like to find out things now, and I think - both my brother and I have self-educated ourselves a lot. My brother - he's very well educated, and he left school at thirteen. But he's been i
n for examinations and everything he goes in for he's a hundred out of a hundred. Yes. And when he went in for chemistry, he couldn't - my people could never afford to send him to a hospital like they used to have to do in those days for two years. I've g
o
t a brother-in-law that went - to a hospital for two years, and then they get the letters and they can open a shop. My brother was never able to do that. But he went in for preliminary exams and passed a hundred out of a hundred, he passed a hundred out o
f
 a hundred for first aid. And everything - and yet he's got nothing about him, to look at him you'd think he was the most ordinary person. But there's nothing he don't find out. He made his own musical instruments, and he taught himself to play the violin
,
 went into a - violin band, played the double parts and - him and me used to share - a record between us, he couldn't afford one, nor could I, so we used to buy one between us you know and share it, so that he could hear - whatever was his name now - not 
Samson, somebody - play - the - the double parts they used to play, and so that he could get that you know, the alto and treble on the violin. We used to buy these records so he could - play it. There was no getting him down. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Now about work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, that's it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What was your first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 My first job was - learning domestic machining. It was all to do with the hat trade, but it was domestic machining, 
and - oh it was lovely work, I used to love it. We used to do -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
It was a place called Barnes and Dawson in King Street. And - when you joined there at fourteen you were supposed to stop there for life. But - I was - my sister w
ent when she was fourteen, and of course I had to follow suit. A tailoress that used to make us some clothes offered me a job, because I used to win prizes for needlework at school. Best buttonholer, and the best - smocking and all that, used to do a lot 
o
f smocking. And I - I won prizes for all that sort of thing, and these tailoresses asked my mother if I could go there to learn tailoring and they would teach me the trade, which would take about three years, at about one and six a week. And when my mothe
r
 told me I wouldn't go. I said, I'm not going for that money, and I didn't. and so I went for five shillings a week - in the domestic - machining. You had to work a year for five shillings, and then we used to have to - when we wanted a rise at the Christ
m
as, each one in turn had to go knock at the door the bosses office, trembling at your knees, and wait until they said, come in. Then we used to go in and stand - they'd be one side of the counter, you the other. Well? We used to say, well we've come to se
e
, we've been here a year or two years, if we can have a rise. And he'd turn round to me, the man - the boss did, and he said, well, he said, I've had very good reports about you, but, he said - it's two shillings rise each year you know for the girls, but
 
- Miss Large, this was this forelady - forelady, Ginny, yes, she said you've - done so well and you work so fast, that we're going to give you half a crown. But I hadn't got to tell the other girls. Well I didn't like that you know, I hate keeping secrets
. But anyway I had the half a crown. I was thrilled to bits. And we used to have to sit and treadle, do you know what I mean, treadle like this, yes, to do it. Only we used to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you get the job, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh automatically my - my 
sister went there, and I suppose she told them you know about me, and - you automatically - followed on. I think mother had to go and have an interview you know, it was all above board everything those days. You couldn't just sort of nip in anywhere. Then
 
another lady - the lady next door to us used to do hats, and I used to help her trim her hats, then take them into the - warehouse, and the lady was ever so nice and she said to me, are you coming to work for me when you leave school? So I said, yes, I th
ink I will. And it was opposite the park, and I really fancied going working for her, but - in the end I went in the domestic machining.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think because your mother wanted you to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well in those days we did really have to do what we were told
 more or less. And I think some - some - girls could rebel with their mothers more than I could. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Before you left school you had little part time jobs did you,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 While I was at school? Oh I used to take - hats for a lady. I used to help t
he lady that side do her hats and take them, she used to give me shilling a week, if I washed up and did all her cleaning her kitchen, and clean her knives and forks, we used to have to clean all our knives and forks when we were kids with whitening and a
s
hes out of the hearth. There was no such thing as a tin of Wim, or anything like that. And I used to clean all her cutlery, and clean all her scullery and everything, and she used to give me an extra sixpence. Then I used to take me grandad's shoes home, 
he used to give me sixpence, and a - and either an apple or - or something nice you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How long would these have taken you, when did you fit them in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh, we used to go soon as we'd had our tea every day. To the - to the factories. And I used to take my mother's too. Take hers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you do it at weekends as well, not Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Not Sundays, - never Sunday, no. Saturdays, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you feel that you were getting paid fairly for doing things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I think we were thrilled with a
 bob. As long as I could buy something - well - in those days you could buy a quarter of - I always remember, Dunn's chocolate for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 pence ha'penny. Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
pence ha'penny a quarter. And they used to do them in big blocks about as big as the top of that 
- microphone. And they used to stick a - point in to break it up. And I used to be thrilled to death watching 'em do that, you know. And I used to have my quarter of chocolate pretty often. My Dunn's chocolate, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you mind doing these jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, I used to love it. Used to love it. I used to love when they used to let me do the hats, because - and afterwards I could see that it taught me to drape - and to - to stick and all sorts of jobs that came easily to me. I didn't see it at the time, I 
was just pleased to help them, you know, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Did it alter your attitude to school when you were doing jobs and earning money at the same time as going to school, did you feel that you would be better employed doing some work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well you - weren'
t allowed to work, I don't think my mother would have allowed us to have taken a job. These were all sort of - helping people out and treats if you know what I mean. Treating you for doing it, yes. Because you see - women that did hats - while you were ta
king their hats, they would probably be getting a meal ready, or doing - some washing or ironing or something. Nearly all the kids - used to run errands and do jobs you know while their mothers were busy. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What sort of hours did you work in your first job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 From eight in the morning 'til twelve. One 'til four. Back at five until eight at night. For five shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you work Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Saturday mornings we used to get an extra - shilling. I think it was. It was penny an hour
 that we had. For an hour. And if we worked Saturday mornings I think we used to get an extra shillings. Had to work right until one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have a half day during the week at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you get holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you feel your wage was a fair one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes. Because it was regular, we was always taught then that if you'd got a regular job, you knew what you'd got coming in, you knew what you could spend and - I only used to have sixpence out of my five shi
llings. Sixpence and the rest went to mum. She straight way bought a bedroom suite when I started work. Yes. She had - in those days - what they called Satin Walnut, it was light wood like this but it was - really lovely wood. And - I always remember in l
ater years -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 So she spent the money that you gave her on sort of extra things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 On the furniture, yes, on the furniture, yes. I think - mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You've forgotten what you were sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 ing about later years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I have, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you get on with the people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Very well. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You were a happy lot were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did your employer treat you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Pretty well, you know, those that behaved, those that didn't work were soon out on their heels. Mm. And 
there were dirty girls then, at work, mm. Yes, it was at the time when Luton imported a lot of Scotch people, you know, we had the - what they called the Scotch colony come here. I don't know if it was just after the war started, it was when I was first a
t work when I was young, and they were lousy. Mm. They all grew up - they all grew up after they got here to have nice homes and got on. I think Luton's a good place for workers you know. But - yes, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you avoid them at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No I don't think so, I don't think so, 'cos we all had to work together and - you know, such a busy life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How did you and the other girls feel about your employer, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well we was always in awe of them. Yes. They always let you know that they we
re the bosses and - you was the underdog. Yes. If you passed on the stairs or anything you'd always step back, and let them go forward, all that sort of thing, and the foreman used to stand in the doorway every morning, with his watch in his hand like thi
s. Yes. And he'd say good}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
morning to everybody as they walked in, good morning. And if anyone was in and it was half a minute past eight, oh you'd get a telling off. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You liked the work did you, how did you feel about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well some of th
e work I used to like and some I didn't. I didn't like - when we used to have - we used to put a lot of padding in stuff, and it was wadding, you know what wadding is do you, a wool}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 l}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 y material - like kapock - filling, only - this wadding was so fine and fl
uffy, and we used to have unbleached and white, all the best work and the best white wadding, and the cheap work the unbleached, and when we had to do the unbleached we hated it. 'Cos it was browny looking, and got all little bits of fleck in it you know,
 I used to hate that. But the white, oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where would the wadding go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Wadding - in the - in the - sometimes we used to - have a piece of net like that, with a piece of satin, it was all cut - to size and you had to - put it like that and sti
tch it down, then turn it this way, put your wadding in, for padding, like that, so that when it was finished it stood up lovely in the middle, you see, yes. And then we did - what they called - half inch pleats. You had a - long piece of satin cut on the
 
cross, with a little white tip, what we called a tip and you started exactly at the middle, you had to start - start exactly in the middle there, start - and as it went round as quick as lightning you was pleating. And every pleat had to be - regular, but
 
you got so used to it that you could almost do it with your eyes shut, as it went round like this you was pleating all the way and as you got back, the end piece, there was just enough to come over where you started, and we had to one gross an hour. One g
ross an hour every day that we did them. And if you didn't d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 o your gross an hour - you'd co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 p it. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you get fed up with doing the same thing over and over again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, used to love it. Used to like some work - some better than other you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It needed a lot of concentration?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
And then they asked us - the forelady asked us once if we could - think of any design - to do - as a different thing you know. And of course there was me, I was eyes all over the place going backwards and forw
ards to work, and I done three or four designs with silk stitching work. And they took on, we did grosses and grosses and grossed of them, but you never ever got a thank you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you get paid for your ideas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No, not in those days, no. You were just lucky if they took anything off of you and - thought it was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What was silk stitching work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Silk stitching, well I used to do - sometimes they were crosses. And one was a sort of - steps, coming down, and of course you had to do
 them level at the side of the satin, you know, it was an extra piece of - sort of - finish. Then we used to have little -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 These were just finishing bits inside the hat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Inside the hat, yes. And then we used to do - in men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 s hats we used to do -
 these padded satin interior, what they called the lining, and then - there would be a little stamp put at the top, printed, they used to print them in a machine like printing - paper, but it was satin, a little - probably a little gold or black ring, the
n
 we had what they called convex mirrors. By the grosses they used to come in gross boxes. And all these mirrors were convex, you know what I mean, and we had to tie - very narrow braid on these convex mirrors, we used to hold them close to us like that, d
o - and tie little bows - dear little two little bows and two little ends and cut them and we used to do grosses and grosses and grosses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where did they go then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Then they had to stitch them on the satin, stitch them through, top and bottom and 
each side, and then sometimes there used to be a little slot made to put a comb through. So there was a teeny little comb, and a little mirror, inside of these men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 s hats, we used to do those, yes. Mm. And then as the war went on, we did - soldiers helmets
, that the soldiers used to go to - Egypt, you know where it was very hot weather, and we made the helmets for those. Well then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 They were straw were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I was getting twelve shillings a week at that time, I'd been there four years nearly. An
d - I was getting twelve shillings a week, or twelve and six a week, I think my sister was getting about a pound a week. Well of course she'd have been satisfied for life, but I wasn't. I was hearing about girls doing war work and earning more money. I wa
s
 thinking of my mother. And what she could do with and what I could do with. And so I decided I'd like to leave. Of course there was a row at home. But in the end I won. Yes, I had the interview. And passed me interview. It was in the Admiralty. The Admir
alty opened up a department in Luton, and there was the - head ones came down from Sheffield - the chief Admiralty place to interview us, and I got the job. Starting at twenty-four shillings a week, twice what I was getting, not so many hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
And - I'll tell you in a minute, and if you served the first month, and you passed, your money was doubled. So of course I told my mother and I think that swayed her a little bit, anyway I got in the Admiralty. Got on like a house af
ire, I loved it. And the - big Commander Jackson used to come down in all his full - regalia uniform to teach us - all about these fuses, naval fuses you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Is that what you were making?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, they weren't made, they had a department at Kent, an
d a - a department at the Vauxhall, where they had a section of people belonging to the Admiralty making these shells and testing them and passing them out. Then they used to come back to the Bute Street centre, some of them, small parts, and all the smal
l parts - to be - put together, and tested. Well then I was made over}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
looker over a whole bench of girls, over a floor of girls, and I used to have to watch them work to see that they did them right with the gauges and all the different things, reamers, we used to ream round - things, you know, it was real men}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
s - type of engineering, I loved every minute of it. So interesting. And there used to be a man, he was a - actually a tobacconist, he joined the Admiralty, and he used to - cut the fuses, well - for m
e he did, he cut the fuses to show me - all the insides when they were cut in half. I had mine for years. Mm. I loved it, yes, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 How long did you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I did that - for about eight or nine months and then I was transferred to Kent, over - some people at Kent. And then it in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 That was an engineering firm was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, a big engineering firm. Then we had fun, 'cos it was all men up there. Oh lovely it was, the men used to - little holes in the partitions, used to put notes t
hrough you know and all that sort of thing. We really had a lovely time up there. But it entailed night work, and I didn't like that. My mother used to be worried. Well I was earning such good money my sister decided it was time she left. So she left and 
t
hen of course she got in an awful row and I got into a row for - they thought I'd kidded her on to come. Then a friend of hers came. Then the head girl came. And then nearly all the bench came, there were about eight of us all together, all good workers f
rom this place come to the Admiralty. Of course they were all earning good money, they all loved it. I got into trouble for that 'cos they thought I started the ball rolling, which I suppose I did really, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you do what you'd call an apprenticeship for any of your jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well - the apprenticeship really was the - yes, that was an apprenticeship, yes. I don't remember if they sign anything, I don't think they did, I think it was just an agreed - matter of - verbal agreement you know, that - we
ll it was a recognized thing, everyone that started there - they had to sort of be a good needle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12656273\charrsid14287120 -wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
man to start with, and if they got on in the first or month or two they were supposed to be there 'til they was married or - for life. Mm. And some of 'em did, they stayed years and years and years. And I think old Ginny stopped until she died. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you belong to any sort of trade union or professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Not at that time, no. That came on - after - just after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did you do after you left the Admiralty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I went back on the - hat machining, not to the same place. I went to this place that I'm telling you where this nice - gentleman was, Mr Warran. He'd got a factory and in those days they were importing Jews into th
e country. And that was the time when the first lot of Jews all came to England. Some of 'em, came to Luton and they were poor. They used to live in basements, like these Pakistanis are living now, and the cooking and the windows were - filthy. You never 
s
aw - people used to hate the Jews, but they always got the top jobs. They was clever. And they could always do things in the hat trade that - Luton people either couldn't or wouldn't do, or couldn't do quick enough or good enough or something, they were a
l
ways at the top, so you was always working for a Jew. And he - they used to open - what they call a new department in these that factories, for doing all this stitched work. Well of course me being used to doing this stitching, didn't take me very long to
 get back into it. And my sister came with me there, we both went from the Admiralty there. And I got a rise before she did there. Yes. She was ever so mad about that. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 That was after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 After the war. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did you do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Did all these lovely - stitched hats, we used to do - stitched tops, stitched bands round and round stitching, then you had to stitch the band to the top, then you make a brim, and stitch the brim - I used to do the fixing a lot, fix the top to the bo
ttom, and then put them on a block and shape them all you know, very nice hats they were. And the Jews used to turn so many - hundreds of dozens of - out a week, cheap, that they used to make a packet of money for the bosses they were working for. And the
y demanded it theirselves and got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Would they have been sort of middle men then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well they were hired to - to - open department. I went from there, I don't know whether they closed down - or whether I went to better meself to another place - w
here they did - and a Jew boy was there. And when I first went to work for him, of course I was only young, and he was only young. Well in later years I worked for his son, and I used to meet the father at parties, and he owned a huge factory in Luton. Hu
ge factory in London, he used to - backwards and forwards to America. And never seen anything like it. He asked me to marry him when we was young. I wouldn't look at him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you wish you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No, I don't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 But they were universally disliked were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
They were good bosses. And the Jews used to say, if you was a good worker - and you could do the work you could have the money. And I didn't half earn some money under the Jews. Mm. You could call 'em - you could call 'em - fat headed -
 pigs, you could call 'em 'cos you hated them so much, and they'd just laugh at you, and you must like them - in a way, they - they'd get your wool off your back, and yet you couldn't help liking them. And - if you grumbled, he'd say, well - well, fair en
ough, fair enough, another ha'penny. You}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid287981\charrsid14287120 're worth it, you're not a shy-s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
meiser, they used to call them that didn't work very well you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they mix socially with other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Used to buy champagne. Bring us all motza biscuits in and -
 we used to have parties, yes, and - one Jew bought me - one Jew I worked for him for nine or ten years, and he bought me a lovely wedding present. Mm. Two in fact, a biscuit barrel and a - clock. Wanted to buy me a wall clock and I didn't want one at the
 time. I had a lovely clock and a biscuit barrel with - silver all on it you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What other jobs did you do after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well it was always the hat work. I - I worked - with this old Jew boy I'm telling you about until I had my - Alec. I used to
 go part time after I was married. And - I didn't used to go at eight in the morning like I used to when I was single, I told them that I couldn't, but they wouldn't let me leave and go somewhere else, so I used to go in about ten. Then go home at twelve,
 back at two, and then after two I'd work on - as long as they wanted me to, my hubby used to come and fetch me home you know. Or come and meet me and - used to have bicycles in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you belong to any sort of trade union after the war then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I never did join - a trade union but I worked with trade union people that - were - were the beginnings of the trade unions. Yes. Yes. I remember this one person - turning the motor off and giving us a talk, and we'd all got to join the union, we'd g
ot to stick together and do this and do the other, but I think we were always - in that - time always - we'd rather do it in our own way. Of course the unions have grown since then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you ever take part in any sort of activities that they organised?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you feel that the employers and the workers had the same interests? Or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh well they had different interests, the - the majority of the bosses were either golfers, tennis players - or some such thing, rugby or someth
ing like that, that we were just outside, we was always interested and was always watching, used to - I used to get up at six in the morning and go down to Woodham Park to watch tennis. And I always wanted to play tennis but never did it only just - you k
now, in our own way like. But - oh I used to - I do now, it fascinates me. Oh - sit glued to the wireless when the tournaments are on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think they made their money for the same reason as you made your money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, how they started I don't know, but the - everyone that started in a factory all made money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Started up a factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Started up a factory, all made money. Because in those days, they used to say - supposing you got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid287981\charrsid14287120 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120  three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid287981\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
pence for making a hat, which was a good price for making a hat in those days, you'd get - three shillings or perhaps twelve shillings now for doing the same thing, but in those days three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid287981\charrsid14287120  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 pence was a lot of money, and if you - if you were making three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid287981\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
penny hats, and they went into the town and they didn
't want to buy, they'd offer to do them for half a crown. Offer to get the order for half a crown. Then they'd come back and tell you afterwards, we can get the work if you'll do them for half a crown. It's either half a crown or nothing, so we used to do
 them. Yes. And they always bribed us like that, we were - the workers were always - bribed, we always had to take a cut. Yes, they'd never offer you anything -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you feel that the trade union might be a good idea for fighting against that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Now I do. Now I do, but in those days we didn't - understand about it enough, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think there was a division in those days between trained craftsmen and other sorts of workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well, a trained craftsmen, like my father, other people couldn't
 do it. They couldn't do it if they hadn't been - brought up to do it, they simply wouldn't know how to do it, and if they were taught they probably wouldn't make a craftsman. My father made shoes when he was nine, and they're in a - mus - museum now at L
u
ton. Mm. He used - they used to have competitions in those days. And he was always in a - competition, he'd win for this and win for that and get a prize card and - then he'd keep them and hide them like we do, put them away, nobody'd ever know or ever se
e
 them. And then - they were having an interview - at some time or another and my father was - talking, or my brother was talking to him about something and these shoes came up, and they asked if they could have them in the museum. Well my father was only 
too pleased to let them have them you know. And my brother's got a windmill in the museum, that he made, took him fifteen years to make.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Out of what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Out of - well you haven't got time for me to show you a newspaper, but it's got all the reading
 about it. He made every brick - everything in miniature, scaled down to about - one inch to every yard, of - the thing. Well we used to go for car rides, 'cos he used - he used to have an old van in those days, go round to the - to the - windmill, and he
'
d sketch and do it and then he'd go home and do a bit, he'd all the concrete base he made out of concrete himself, all little - stones and built-that. Then he did all the wood himself, all the shutters, you know the shutters in a windmill, thousands of 'e
m, he cut all those, all the brushes he made out of his son's hair off his head. He soldered - iron workings - well you ought to go and see it if ever you got the chance, it's in the museum, and they made a case for it some years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And it was a replica of an actual windmill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Replica of an actual - windmill that we used to go and visit and - go up land down you know, years before. And he even, at one time - paid - helped to pay and helped to restore one. Yes. And he's written for the Cambridge m
agazines all about wind - call him the windmill man. He painted windmills and - everything. That - that this windmill - how it came about nobody knew about it, it was in his back bedroom, he just did it for a hobby. One night there was a fire. And this fi
r
e - 'cos he was a cameraman as I told you, always taking pictures, everything his old camera was there, out of his window, took a picture of this fire, goes back to bed. Well, the next day - somebody comes and knocks at his door, had he took a picture of 
t
his fire, someone told him that Mr Woodbridge had took a picture of the fire. Oh yes, he said. So he said, could I have it to put in the paper? He said, it had died down be - when we got up - up here. And somebody told us you had taken a picture so - my b
r
other said, oh no, he said, I've got some very very important - pictures on my film, he said, that I couldn't let you have. So the man said, well I'll take great care of them. But they wangled it - I forget whether me brother - did do it for him specially
 
and let him have this fire, it was in the paper. But - he went up to interview my brother about the film and the fire, and spent hours and hours and hours looking at his windmill out of the window where he took it, the bedroom window, took him up to show 
h
im where he took it. Oh the windmill, the windmill. Of course the windmill was the - the whole thing, the windmill was in the paper with all about me brother. He nearly died. And all about - it was so - everybody was so interested you know, and in the end
 they asked him at the museum - if ever he thought of parting with it - would they let them - let him have it. So he said, oh yes, he said, I'll be glad to get rid of it. It's still there so you can always go and see it. And I've got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think in those early days people respected people who had a craft?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 It was a natural craft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think when you were young you wanted to get a craft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 There's no wanting, you - you simply did the things. You - you had the urge to do them and you h
ad to do them and you loved doing them. But if you were told to do them you wouldn't do them. If you were told you - you've got to do this or do the other you wouldn't do it. A natural talent, and I think my mother and my father - had their - interests, a
n
d - and we grew up with it inborn in us. Yes. 'Cos I used to paint on satin, I've embroidered peacocks on satin cushion - cushions, for me mother, and done all sorts of things. Everything that was beautiful, I must get it - over somehow. And nobody stoppe
d me and no - no - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think when you started working full time that your attitude to life changed at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well you certainly had a sense of being somebody and - you thought, you know, well, you know, I'm at work, I'm a person, you know, i
n me own right now, you can - do this or do the other or - mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Do you think - you continued to live at home didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did your parents look in you any differently when you started work full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I think my mother was very proud that we could do our work and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they treat you as more grown up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Oh yes. Yes. And always bought us more clothes then you know. My mother used to say, you know - like 'cos I'd always got me eyes glued if there was a new shop, and 
a coat right in the middle of the window I always wanted it. I used to go home and say to my mother, so - it's only fourteen and eleven mum. A coat that would cost fifteen guineas now used to be fourteen and eleven when I was young. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid287981\charrsid14287120 My mother used to say, no, no, y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
ou can't have it. I always remember one, I said, it's violet with a - little black velvet collar, comes round, I described it, sketched it, drawed it, showed her, try - oh I said, and it's violet colour, I said, oh I would love it. Well evidently 
my mother sneaked down the town and had a look. And - she came - when I came home she said, I've seen the coat, she said, it's very nice. She said, and I'm sure it'd suit you. I said, does that mean I can have it mum? She gave me the fifteen shillings and
 
I went and fetched it. Fitted me perfectly, everything I saw that I wanted - it fitted me. It - automatically clicked as though I knew it was mine. You know. And then I remember seeing another one and it was a tweedy sort of thing, and going home and tell
i
ng my mother. And she bought me that. And I don't think we had an awful lot of clothes but I think - fi they suited us and we liked them she'd buy us them. And she always also bought us a lot of material to make clothes. I can remember making - little sho
r
t monkey jackets, and - she used to teach us how to line them and put canvas all in them. And - you know, they all had to be proper. And you could make a coat for half a crown. The stuff was six three a yard. Beautiful check material and like that. And I 
w
as in a Dutch bazaar once and I made a - red satin skirt, with a white muslin blouses, with a fissure, what they called a fissure, a tabot sort of thing, cut up here, and a little hat that had got a - I cut patterns out you know until I got it - to fit ro
u
nd the face like this, like a Dutch, and we sent my good looking pal that I'm telling you about, and me, we went to Holland, or someone did for us at the chapel, for some real - clogs, we had real Dutch clogs. And I had them until - I was going to America
 and I gave them away. And I used to have - fill them with dirt and have plants in them. I had them all them years. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did your brother and sisters treat you any differently once you were a full time working girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Well I think it was us treated
 them different, I suppose we thought we could boss them about you know, yes. I think we must have done you know. 'Cos I remember my brother once - when I took a friend in the house, I wasn't very old and - this is the one that cried because she wanted to
 
come to school with me, when she grew up she was rather frumpy because she lived with an old grandma, and she used to have nice clothes but rather frumpy, she always looked as if she was blown up sort of frumpy, I think she had a lot of things underneath,
 you know, and - always remember my brother saying, don't you bring her in here. I said to him, you mind your own business, I said - she'll come in if I like. You know. And - that was when - when I'd just started work. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you spend your Sunday any differently after you'd started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, I think - we always used to go and listen to the band, when the band played in the town. 'Cos I'd got a cousin and an uncle that played in the band. And my mother - and - that family were very friendly, the
y were always - either at our house, or we were at their house, and my friend - used to like him, and I used to like his pal. And I used to do a lot of work for the Army, fancy work, and so we always got an invitation to the does there, so of course there
 
was four of us always together, the two boys and the two girls. And they used to come whistle up the school playground, you know, for us. Yes, 'cos we got told off about that. And the mayor - and the mayors son used to live near us, like where we lived in
 Talbot Road, was on a corner, and just along a little street was the mayor's house on the corner there and they had greenhouses with orchids, and he used to walk me home and give me orchids out of his greenhouse. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you take an interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
No, I don't think so. Only - on the day of the - mm - elections you know. I think we used to have a bit of blue ribbon, blue and yellow ribbon and - I don't remember ever being deliberate Liberals, but my father was a Liberal and I suppos
e we just followed him, you know. No, I think it was the pretty ribbon and the hunting and all that that really - persuade us you know, it wasn't the politician I don't think. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did - the way you spent your spare time after you started work change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Well yes. Because - there was a friend where I worked that was - a very nice - type of person, I've never met a person like her before, that used to go to - amateur dramatics, she used to write poetry, and was a very - booky sort of girl, looking bac
k, she was a very nice girl and she used to invite me, would I like to go - these places with her, and I used to go. So of course that was an entire change. I used to sing in the - choirs, the Co-op choir and the school choir. But these affairs what we us
ed to go with her were - in a different room, evening - yes, in the evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 And you liked that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Yes, I used to like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 That was something you hadn't come across before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 That's right, yes, something new. And - you know, sort o
f - we used to get - clothes, special clothes you know and all like that, of course I used to like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You used to bring friends home didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh yes. Always - all our friends and all our boys my mother always had home. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did you have to be in by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
Yes, definitely. Yes. Ten o'clock. Every night. When I first started courting I was eighteen and a half - and I'd been courting some months, before my mother met him, and we were canoodling just round the corner of
 where we lived one night when they came home from the theatre, which was about half past ten. And - I said, oh I said, if my mother and father come in now, I said, I shall cop it, you know, out - being out. So he said, oh, he said, don't worry, he said, 
you've got nothing to worry about. I said, no, but I said, look at the time. So they came walking along arm in arm, and my father looked and he said, oh, so you're the young}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid287981\charrsid14287120  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 man that's keeping my daughter out late. He said, ten o'clock's her time wherever s
he goes and whoever she goes with, as long as she's home by ten that's all right. So - it wasn't long after that before my boyfriend was calling 'em ma and pa and - everything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Did they like to know where you were as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh - always had to te
ll them where we was. Yes. Yes. He used - they used to say we don't mind where you go as long as we know who you're with and where you're going. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 You tell me about some things you thought of then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh - about the park, it took a - big part in
 our life, the - Warroiund Park. I can remember that before the lake was actually made like it is now, it was - sort - in it's raw state you know, and they used to have a little - paddling pool and sand where we used to go and play, and on - exhibition da
ys, when they used to have the - flower show, where my father used to show his sweet peas and that, they used to have a - a big life boat brought into the town, on the lake you know. And - we used to go - we used to go -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Where did it come from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 
I don't know. Must have come from a - coast - Southsea or Portsmouth, somewhere down that way. It was a lifeboat and of course they were different in those days to what they are now, it was just a sort of a - a rounded side boat, you know, huge thing i
t was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Were you allowed to go on it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 I think we used to go on it for trips, and we was always on the little boat down there, you know, you could always go on the little boats.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What about these pease pudding suppers,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 Oh, when - when I 
first - this was when I was first courting, we used to go down to my boy's - all her children, one night a week, either Friday or Saturday, we used to have beer, 'cos they had a lot of beer down there, beer and she used to make faggots in a big tin, like 
that, and pease pudding, and that and we all had these faggots and pease pudding. We used to have some fun down there, they were a jolly family. Mm. Ever so jolly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1580481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 What did your husband's father do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3765441 EP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367996\charrsid14287120 He was - he'd got a very good job in the Haywa
rds Tylers Foundry where my boy was open - apprenticed. My hubby was apprenticed there. Because they used to sort of follow on the father's footsteps you know, and - his father was a pattern maker, in the brass turning - they used to do all ships' engines
 
and - bottling machines and that you know. He worked there, I think it was sixty-seven years, I've got a newspaper cutting where they - presented him with war bonds when he left, and he sang a little song to them, 'cos they were ever such a jolly family. 
P
arties galore. The grandfather used to have a great big house, 'cos they were - business people, his grandparents were. And they used to have this great big house, we used to go up there and I can remember - the rooms were so big that when you danced, abo
u
t twenty of us in a room, the floor and the sides used to go. It was a huge house. And my boy, before - I met him, they used to have a skating rink at the top of the house, they all used to go skating round the top. It was made into a big nursing home aft
erwards. Yes.
